                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/477<hi rend="superscript">3</hi>/<hi
                        rend="sub">6</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. G. Frederick Reinhardt of
                        the Division of European Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-09-30">September 30,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Harry Hopkins,<note n="16" xml:id="d406fn16"
                                >Harry L. Hopkins, Special Assistant to the President.</note> Mr.
                                Acheson,<note n="17" xml:id="d406fn17">Dean G. Acheson, Assistant
                                Secretary of State.</note> of the Department of State, and other
                            members of the President’s Soviet Protocol Committee</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>During the course of the Committee meeting, Mr. Hopkins referred to the question
                    of supplies for Iran. He stated that General Connolly was operating in that area
                    under a directive which instructed him to subordinate all other matters to the
                    prime consideration of getting supplies through to the Soviet Union. This had
                    given rise to certain conflict with other agencies of this Government which were
                    operating in Iran.</p>
                <p>Mr. Hopkins suggested that the whole question be examined with a view to the
                    possible issuance of modified instructions to General Connolly, should this
                    prove to be required by American policy in that area.</p>
            </div>
